 = \n| medaltemplates = \n}}\n'''Alfredo Moreno Cano''' (born {{birth date|1981|06|23|df=yes}}) is a Spanish male  [[Track cycling|track cyclist]], riding for the national team. He competed in the team sprint event at the [[2010 UCI Track Cycling World Championships]].<ref>{{cite web|title=2010 Track Cycling World Championships: Entries list|url=http://www.tissottiming.com/File/Download?id=0003010002FFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFF00|publisher=tissottiming.com|accessdate=1 February 2016}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.cyclingarchives.com/coureurfiche.php?coureurid=22462 Profile] at ''cyclingarchives.com''\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Moreno Cano, Alfredo}}\n[[Category:1981 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Spanish track cyclists]]\n[[Category:Spanish male cyclists]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n{{Spain-cycling-bio-1980s-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Lepricavark", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:added short description", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alfredo_Moreno_Ca%C3%B1o"}
{"title_page": "Pira-pirasong Pangarap", "text_new": "{{short description|Philippine television and radio show}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2018}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name = Pira-pirasong Pangarap\n| genre = [[Drama (film and television)|Drama]]\n| picture_format = [[480i]] ([[SDTV]])\n| runtime = 30 minutes\n| company = [[Sampaguita Pictures|Sampaguita Television]]\n| developer = Marichu Maceda\n| director = {{plainlist|\n* '''TV'''\n* [[Gina Alajar]]\n* Manny Casta\u00f1eda\n* [[Albert Martinez]]\n* Soxy Topacio\n* Ruel Bayani\n* Jeffrey Jeturian\n* Joey Romero\n* [[Khryss Adalia]]\n* '''Radio'''\n* Lucio Maylas}}\n| executive_producer = {{plain list|\n* Jo-Ann Banaga {{small|(TV)}}\n* Gypsy Baldovino {{small|(radio)}}}}\n| presenter = [[Gina de Venecia]]\n| opentheme = \"Pira-pirasong Pangarap\" by Dulce\n| country = [[Philippines]]\n| location = Philippines\n| language = [[Tagalog language|Tagalog]]\n| network = [[GMA Network]]\n| camera = [[Multiple-camera setup]]\n| first_aired = {{plainlist|\n* June 1996 {{small|(radio)}}\n* {{start date|1997|8|18}} {{small|(TV)}}}}\n| last_aired = {{end date|2003|2|21}}\n}}\n\n'''''Pira-pirasong Pangarap''''' ({{translation|Pieces of Dreams}}) is a [[Philippine television drama]] anthology broadcast by [[GMA Network]]. It also aired on [[DZBB-AM|Super Radyo DZBB]]. Hosted by [[Gina de Venecia]], it premiered on August 18, 1997.<ref>http://archives.manilatimes.net/national/2009/may/10/yehey/weekend/20090510week1.html{{Dead link|date=December 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> The show concluded on February 21, 2003. It was replaced by ''[[Nagmamahal, Manay Gina]]'' in its timeslot.\n\n==Overview==\n{{multiple image\n|direction = vertical\n|align = left\n|image1 = Gina de Venecia (cropped).jpg\n|caption1 = Gina de Venecia serves as a host.\n|width1 = 150\n}}\n\nThe plight of battered women and children whose lives were transformed by ''The Haven for Women'' (an establishment of the nine-building in Alabang. It was inaugurated in September 30, 1995. Its main goal is to rehabilitate the abused women and help them to reclaim their God-given right to live with dignity) served as inspiration for her to come up a radio drama program entitled ''Pira-pirasong Pangarap'', launched in June 1996 on [[DZRH]]. The following year, the TV version made its debut on [[GMA Network]]. This also the radio drama to moved from DZRH to [[DZBB-AM|Super Radyo DZBB]], the AM radio station of GMA Network. During its run, the show raked in five Best Drama Series trophies from the Philippine Movie Press Club's (PMPC) Star Award.<ref name=\"philstar1\">http://www.philstar.com/Article.aspx?articleId=92151{{Dead link|date=May 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref name=\"philstar2\">http://www.philstar.com/Article.aspx?articleId=135978{{Dead link|date=May 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:GMA Network shows]]\n[[Category:Philippine anthology television series]]\n[[Category:1997 Philippine television series debuts]]\n[[Category:2003 Philippine television series endings]]\n[[Category:Filipino-language television programs]]\n\n{{Philippines-tv-prog-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Philippine television and radio show}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2018}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name = Pira-pirasong Pangarap\n| genre = [[Drama (film and television)|Drama]]\n| picture_format = [[480i]] ([[SDTV]])\n| runtime = 30 minutes\n| company = [[Sampaguita Pictures|Sampaguita Television]]\n| developer = Marichu Maceda\n| director = {{plainlist|\n* '''TV'''\n* [[Gina Alajar]]\n* Manny Casta\u00f1eda\n* [[Albert Martinez]]\n* Soxy Topacio\n* Ruel Bayani\n* Jeffrey Jeturian\n* Joey Romero\n* [[Khryss Adalia]]\n* '''Radio'''\n* Lucio Maylas}}\n| executive_producer = {{plain list|\n* Jo-Ann Banaga {{small|(TV)}}\n* Gypsy Baldovino {{small|(radio)}}}}\n| presenter = [[Gina de Venecia]]\n| opentheme = \"Pira-pirasong Pangarap\" by Dulce\n| country = [[Philippines]]\n| location = Philippines\n| language = [[Tagalog language|Tagalog]]\n| network = [[GMA Network]]\n| camera = [[Multiple-camera setup]]\n| first_aired = {{plainlist|\n* June 1996 {{small|(radio)}}\n* {{start date|1997|8|18}} {{small|(TV)}}}}\n| last_aired = {{end date|2003|2|21}}\n}}\n\n'''''Pira-pirasong Pangarap''''' ({{literal translation|Pieces of Dreams}}) is a [[Philippine television drama]] anthology broadcast by [[GMA Network]]. It also aired on [[DZBB-AM|Super Radyo DZBB]]. Hosted by [[Gina de Venecia]], it premiered on August 18, 1997.<ref>http://archives.manilatimes.net/national/2009/may/10/yehey/weekend/20090510week1.html{{Dead link|date=December 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> The show concluded on February 21, 2003. It was replaced by ''[[Nagmamahal, Manay Gina]]'' in its timeslot.\n\n==Overview==\n{{multiple image\n|direction = vertical\n|align = left\n|image1 = Gina de Venecia (cropped).jpg\n|caption1 = Gina de Venecia serves as a host.\n|width1 = 150\n}}\n\nThe plight of battered women and children whose lives were transformed by ''The Haven for Women'' (an establishment of the nine-building in Alabang. It was inaugurated in September 30, 1995. Its main goal is to rehabilitate the abused women and help them to reclaim their God-given right to live with dignity) served as inspiration for her to come up a radio drama program entitled ''Pira-pirasong Pangarap'', launched in June 1996 on [[DZRH]]. The following year, the TV version made its debut on [[GMA Network]]. This also the radio drama to moved from DZRH to [[DZBB-AM|Super Radyo DZBB]], the AM radio station of GMA Network. During its run, the show raked in five Best Drama Series trophies from the Philippine Movie Press Club's (PMPC) Star Award.<ref name=\"philstar1\">http://www.philstar.com/Article.aspx?articleId=92151{{Dead link|date=May 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref name=\"philstar2\">http://www.philstar.com/Article.aspx?articleId=135978{{Dead link|date=May 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:GMA Network shows]]\n[[Category:Philippine anthology television series]]\n[[Category:1997 Philippine television series debuts]]\n[[Category:2003 Philippine television series endings]]\n[[Category:Filipino-language television programs]]\n\n{{Philippines-tv-prog-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Hotwiki", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fixed", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pira-pirasong_Pangarap"}
{"title_page": "Adam Carse", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2019}}\n{{EngvarB|date=August 2019}}\n'''Adam Von Ahnen  Carse''' (19 May 1878 &ndash; 2 November 1958) was an English composer, academic, music writer and editor, best known for his music for strings and piano, often suitable for student orchestras and beginners, as well as for his studies on the history of instruments and the orchestra. His collection of around 350 antique wind instruments in now in the [[Horniman Museum]].<ref>Grove Music Online</ref>\n\nBorn in [[Newcastle upon Tyne]], Carse was educated in [[Hanover]] and was a Macfarren scholar at the [[Royal Academy of Music]], London where he studied composition with [[Frederick Corder]]. He received the 1902 medal from the [[Worshipful Company of Musicians]], handed to the best student of the academy.<ref>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=The Worshipful Academy of Music |day_of_week=Wednesday |date=29 October 1902 |page_number=8 |issue=36911| }}</ref> He later taught music at Winchester College (1909\u201322), then returning to the Academy as Professor of Harmony and Counterpoint until 1940.<ref>[https://www.chandos.net/chanimages/Booklets/NA5070.pdf Lane, Philip. Notes to ''English String Miniatures Volume 4'', Naxos 5070 (2002)]</ref> In later life Carse concentrated on writing and editing. His books include ''Musical Wind Instruments'' (1939), ''The Orchestra in the 18th Century'' (1940) and ''The Orchestra from Beethoven to Berlioz'' (1948). (An earlier book, ''The History of Orchestration'' (1925), was reissued in a [[Dover Books]] edition in 1964 and 2012).<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books/about/The_History_of_Orchestration.html?id=a3kHvB4fOnYC&redir_esc=y Google Books]</ref> He also specialised in editing early classical symphonies by composers such as [[Carl Friedrich Abel]], [[Thomas Arne]], [[Johann Christian Bach|J C Bach]], [[Fran\u00e7ois-Joseph Gossec|Gossec]] and [[Johann Stamitz|Stamitz]].<ref>Grove Music Online</ref> In February 1945 his son, Edward Adam Carse, was killed in action.<ref>[https://www.flickr.com/photos/sherborneschoolarchives/9414952320 Sherborne School Book of Remembrance]</ref>\n\n===Composition===\nWhile Carse is perhaps best known for his study of the history of instruments and the orchestra, much of the material he wrote and arranged for school orchestras, young string players and pianists is still in use today. His many works for strings included the ''Two Sketches'' of 1924, which were performed at the [[Proms]] on 4 September 1924,<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/events/evwq2m BBC Proms archive]</ref><ref>[https://www.chandos.net/products/catalogue/NA%205070 ''English String Miniatures Volume 4'', Naxos 5070 (2002)]</ref> and the five movement ''Winton Suite'' of 1933, showing the influence of eighteenth century dance suites.<ref>[https://www.chandos.net/products/catalogue/NA%207753 ''English String Miniatures, Volume 6'', Naxos 7753 (2006)]</ref> The seven ''Variations for Strings'' were composed in 1953 and broadcast by the BBC on 10 May 1954.<ref>[https://genome.ch.bbc.co.uk/095025a39c6a4f94ba62de286f08cb35 ''Radio Times'' Issue 1591, 7 May 1954, p 16]</ref> Among his educational piano works is the short ''Miniature Scherzo'', which was chosen as one of ten test pieces for the [[Daily Express]] national piano playing competition in 1928, and recorded as a demonstration by [[William Murdoch]].<ref>[http://www.musicweb-international.com/classrev/2019/Oct/Murdoch_Columbia_6029.htm MusicWeb International]</ref>\n\nEarly orchestral works included a prelude to [[Byron]]'s ''[[Manfred]]''<ref>[https://www.bach-cantatas.com/Lib/Carse-Adam.htm bach-cantatas.com]</ref> and two symphonic poems: ''The Death of Tintagiles'' (1902) and ''[[In a Balcony]]'', (after [[Robert Browning|Browning]]) the latter performed at the Proms on 26 August 1905.<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/events/ed8xn3 BBC Proms archive]</ref> He wrote five symphonies,<ref>[http://www.unsungcomposers.com/forum/index.php?topic=7276.0 Unsung Composers forum]</ref> the second, in G minor, premiered by the orchestra of the [[Royal College of Music]] in London in November 1908 with the composer conducting,<ref>{{cite journal|title=The Musical Times|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=qpUPAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA798|date=1 December 1908|publisher=Novello|accessdate=June 28, 2012|location=London}}</ref> and the third (in F major, composed in 1927) was performed by the [[Bournemouth Municipal Orchestra]] on 20 April 1932 and broadcast from the Bournemouth Pavilion by the BBC.<ref>[https://genome.ch.bbc.co.uk/page/fe27e6b014e04bd0b6289961e4d2e53a6,%2017%20April%201932,%20p%2039 ''Radio Times'', Issue 446, 17 April 1932, p 39]</ref> Carse also wrote chamber music, including a Violin Sonata published in 1921<ref>[https://imslp.org/wiki/Violin_Sonata_(Carse%2C_Adam) Violin Sonata, published Augener 1921, IMSLP]</ref> and the ''Miniature String Quartet'' in A minor, published in 1934.<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books/about/Miniature_string_quartet.html?id=_iv0AAAAMAAJ&redir_esc=y Google Books]</ref> For his compositions Carse occasionally used the name William Kent as an alias, and sometimes Adam Ahn-Carse.<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=yj5jAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA950&lpg=PA950&dq=%22Adam+Carse%22+%22William+Kent%22&source=bl&ots=0JOgSqUI24&sig=ACfU3U1ZXI0jO6fkKs2Uw0FmSeHakeBkfQ&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjsgsvjgrflAhWWiVwKHcGCArAQ6AEwA3oECAkQAQ#v=onepage&q=%22Adam%20Carse%22%20%22William%20Kent%22&f=false ''Catalog of Copyright Entries, Musical Compositions, Part 3'' Library of Congress, 1944]</ref>\n\nCarse died in 1958 at his home - Winton, Martin's End Lane, [[Great Missenden]], [[Buckinghamshire]] - aged eighty.<ref>Obituary, ''Musical Times'' No 1390, December 1958, p 677</ref><ref>Halfpenny, Eric. \"Adam Carse, 1878-1958\", in ''The Galpin Society Journal'', Vol. 12 (May, 1959), pp. 6-7</ref>\n\n== Donation to the Horniman ==\nIn 1947 he donated his collection of 350 wind instruments to the [[Horniman Museum]] in South London in memory of his son Edward Adam (Peter) Carse, and there is a plaque commemorating his gift in the Horniman Music Gallery.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://lewishamwarmemorials.wikidot.com/memorial:forest-hill-horniman-museum-music-gallery|title=Forest Hill, Horniman Museum Music Gallery - Lewisham War Memorials|website=lewishamwarmemorials.wikidot.com|access-date=2016-08-01}}</ref> He dedicated his Fifth Symphony, written in June 1945, to the memory of his son.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://lewishamwarmemorials.wikidot.com/person:carse-edward-adam|title=Carse, Edward Adam MBE - Lewisham War Memorials|website=lewishamwarmemorials.wikidot.com|access-date=2016-08-01}}</ref>\n\nAlongside the donated instruments is the personal library of Adam Carse, containing research papers, manuscript notes, copies of lectures, correspondence, makers catalogues, sales lists and concert programmes.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.horniman.ac.uk/collections/archives/|title=Archives - Collections - Horniman Museum and Gardens|last=Gardens|first=The Horniman Museum and|website=www.horniman.ac.uk|access-date=2016-08-01}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Carse, Adam}}\n[[Category:English classical composers]]\n[[Category:English Romantic composers]]\n[[Category:1878 births]]\n[[Category:1958 deaths]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the Royal Academy of Music]]\n[[Category:English male classical composers]]\n[[Category:20th-century classical composers]]\n[[Category:People from Newcastle upon Tyne]]\n[[Category:20th-century English musicians]]\n[[Category:20th-century British composers]]\n[[Category:20th-century British male musicians]]\n[[Category:19th-century male musicians]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2019}}\n{{EngvarB|date=August 2019}}\n'''Adam Von Ahnen  Carse''' (19 May 1878 &ndash; 2 November 1958) was an English composer, academic, music writer and editor, best known for his music for strings and piano, often suitable for student orchestras and beginners, as well as for his studies on the history of instruments and the orchestra. His collection of around 350 antique wind instruments in now in the [[Horniman Museum]].<ref>Grove Music Online</ref>\n\nBorn in [[Newcastle upon Tyne]], Carse was educated in [[Hanover]] and was a Macfarren scholar at the [[Royal Academy of Music]], London where he studied composition with [[Frederick Corder]]. He received the 1902 medal from the [[Worshipful Company of Musicians]], handed to the best student of the academy.<ref>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=The Worshipful Academy of Music |day_of_week=Wednesday |date=29 October 1902 |page_number=8 |issue=36911| }}</ref> He later taught music at Winchester College (1909\u201322), then returning to the Academy as Professor of Harmony and Counterpoint until 1940.<ref>[https://www.chandos.net/chanimages/Booklets/NA5070.pdf Lane, Philip. Notes to ''English String Miniatures Volume 4'', Naxos 5070 (2002)]</ref> In later life Case concentrated on writing and editing. His books include ''Musical Wind Instruments'' (1939), ''The Orchestra in the 18th Century'' (1940) and ''The Orchestra from Beethoven to Berlioz'' (1948). (An earlier book, ''The History of Orchestration'' (1925), was reissued in a [[Dover Books]] edition in 1964 and 2012).<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books/about/The_History_of_Orchestration.html?id=a3kHvB4fOnYC&redir_esc=y Google Books]</ref> He also specialised in editing early classical symphonies by composers such as [[Carl Friedrich Abel]], [[Thomas Arne]], [[Johann Christian Bach|J C Bach]], [[Fran\u00e7ois-Joseph Gossec|Gossec]] and [[Johann Stamitz|Stamitz]].<ref>Grove Music Online</ref> In February 1945 his son, Edward Adam Carse, was killed in action.<ref>[https://www.flickr.com/photos/sherborneschoolarchives/9414952320 Sherborne School Book of Remembrance]</ref>\n\n===Composition===\nWhile Carse is perhaps best known for his study of the history of instruments and the orchestra, much of the material he wrote and arranged for school orchestras, young string players and pianists is still in use today. His many works for strings included the ''Two Sketches'' of 1924, which were performed at the [[Proms]] on 4 September 1924,<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/events/evwq2m BBC Proms archive]</ref><ref>[https://www.chandos.net/products/catalogue/NA%205070 ''English String Miniatures Volume 4'', Naxos 5070 (2002)]</ref> and the five movement ''Winton Suite'' of 1933, showing the influence of eighteenth century dance suites.<ref>[https://www.chandos.net/products/catalogue/NA%207753 ''English String Miniatures, Volume 6'', Naxos 7753 (2006)]</ref> The seven ''Variations for Strings'' were composed in 1953 and broadcast by the BBC on 10 May 1954.<ref>[https://genome.ch.bbc.co.uk/095025a39c6a4f94ba62de286f08cb35 ''Radio Times'' Issue 1591, 7 May 1954, p 16]</ref> Among his educational piano works is the short ''Miniature Scherzo'', which was chosen as one of ten test pieces for the [[Daily Express]] national piano playing competition in 1928, and recorded as a demonstration by [[William Murdoch]].<ref>[http://www.musicweb-international.com/classrev/2019/Oct/Murdoch_Columbia_6029.htm MusicWeb International]</ref>\n\nEarly orchestral works included a prelude to [[Byron]]'s ''[[Manfred]]''<ref>[https://www.bach-cantatas.com/Lib/Carse-Adam.htm bach-cantatas.com]</ref> and two symphonic poems: ''The Death of Tintagiles'' (1902) and ''[[In a Balcony]]'', (after [[Robert Browning|Browning]]) the latter performed at the Proms on 26 August 1905.<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/events/ed8xn3 BBC Proms archive]</ref> He wrote five symphonies,<ref>[http://www.unsungcomposers.com/forum/index.php?topic=7276.0 Unsung Composers forum]</ref> the second, in G minor, premiered by the orchestra of the [[Royal College of Music]] in London in November 1908 with the composer conducting,<ref>{{cite journal|title=The Musical Times|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=qpUPAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA798|date=1 December 1908|publisher=Novello|accessdate=June 28, 2012|location=London}}</ref> and the third (in F major, composed in 1927) was performed by the [[Bournemouth Municipal Orchestra]] on 20 April 1932 and broadcast from the Bournemouth Pavilion by the BBC.<ref>[https://genome.ch.bbc.co.uk/page/fe27e6b014e04bd0b6289961e4d2e53a6,%2017%20April%201932,%20p%2039 ''Radio Times'', Issue 446, 17 April 1932, p 39]</ref> Carse also wrote chamber music, including a Violin Sonata published in 1921<ref>[https://imslp.org/wiki/Violin_Sonata_(Carse%2C_Adam) Violin Sonata, published Augener 1921, IMSLP]</ref> and the ''Miniature String Quartet'' in A minor, published in 1934.<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books/about/Miniature_string_quartet.html?id=_iv0AAAAMAAJ&redir_esc=y Google Books]</ref> For his compositions Carse occasionally used the name William Kent as an alias, and sometimes Adam Ahn-Carse.<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=yj5jAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA950&lpg=PA950&dq=%22Adam+Carse%22+%22William+Kent%22&source=bl&ots=0JOgSqUI24&sig=ACfU3U1ZXI0jO6fkKs2Uw0FmSeHakeBkfQ&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjsgsvjgrflAhWWiVwKHcGCArAQ6AEwA3oECAkQAQ#v=onepage&q=%22Adam%20Carse%22%20%22William%20Kent%22&f=false ''Catalog of Copyright Entries, Musical Compositions, Part 3'' Library of Congress, 1944]</ref>\n\nCarse died in 1958 at his home - Winton, Martin's End Lane, [[Great Missenden]], [[Buckinghamshire]] - aged eighty.<ref>Obituary, ''Musical Times'' No 1390, December 1958, p 677</ref><ref>Halfpenny, Eric. \"Adam Carse, 1878-1958\", in ''The Galpin Society Journal'', Vol. 12 (May, 1959), pp. 6-7</ref>\n\n== Donation to the Horniman ==\nIn 1947 he donated his collection of 350 wind instruments to the [[Horniman Museum]] in South London in memory of his son Edward Adam (Peter) Carse, and there is a plaque commemorating his gift in the Horniman Music Gallery.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://lewishamwarmemorials.wikidot.com/memorial:forest-hill-horniman-museum-music-gallery|title=Forest Hill, Horniman Museum Music Gallery - Lewisham War Memorials|website=lewishamwarmemorials.wikidot.com|access-date=2016-08-01}}</ref> He dedicated his Fifth Symphony, written in June 1945, to the memory of his son.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://lewishamwarmemorials.wikidot.com/person:carse-edward-adam|title=Carse, Edward Adam MBE - Lewisham War Memorials|website=lewishamwarmemorials.wikidot.com|access-date=2016-08-01}}</ref>\n\nAlongside the donated instruments is the personal library of Adam Carse, containing research papers, manuscript notes, copies of lectures, correspondence, makers catalogues, sales lists and concert programmes.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.horniman.ac.uk/collections/archives/|title=Archives - Collections - Horniman Museum and Gardens|last=Gardens|first=The Horniman Museum and|website=www.horniman.ac.uk|access-date=2016-08-01}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Carse, Adam}}\n[[Category:English classical composers]]\n[[Category:English Romantic composers]]\n[[Category:1878 births]]\n[[Category:1958 deaths]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the Royal Academy of Music]]\n[[Category:English male classical composers]]\n[[Category:20th-century classical composers]]\n[[Category:People from Newcastle upon Tyne]]\n[[Category:20th-century English musicians]]\n[[Category:20th-century British composers]]\n[[Category:20th-century British male musicians]]\n[[Category:19th-century male musicians]]\n", "name_user": "\u0410\u043d\u0434\u0440\u0435\u0439 \u0420\u043e\u043c\u0430\u043d\u0435\u043d\u043a\u043e", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Adam_Carse"}
{"title_page": "GBK (character encoding)", "text_new": "{{short description|Simplified Chinese character encoding}}\n{{refimprove|date=October 2016}}<!-- We need some good GBK 1.0 & 1993 GBK data. All I can find is CP936. -->\n{{Infobox character encoding\n| name = Guojia Biaozhun Kuozhan (GBK)\n| mime = GBK\n| alias = [[Code page 1386|CP936]], MS936, windows-936, csGBK\n| image = GBK encoding.svg\n| caption = Layout of GBK ([[#Layout diagram|see below]] for a larger copy of this diagram)\n| standard = GBK 1.0\n| lang = Primarily used for [[Simplified Chinese]], but also supports [[Traditional Chinese]], [[Japanese language|Japanese]], [[English language|English]], [[Russian language|Russian]] and (partially) [[Greek language|Greek]].\n| status = \n| extends = [[EUC-CN]]\n| prev = [[GB 2312|GB2312]]\n| next = [[GB 18030]]\n| classification = [[Extended ASCII]],{{efn|Not in the strictest sense of the term, as ASCII bytes can appear as trail bytes.}} [[variable-width encoding]], [[CJK|CJK encoding]]\n|extra = <div style=\"text-align: left;\">{{notelist}}</div>\n}}\n'''GBK''' is an extension of the [[GB2312]] [[character set]] for [[Simplified chinese|simplified]] Chinese characters, used in the [[People's Republic of China]]. It includes all unified [[CJK characters]] found in GB13000.1-93, i.e. ISO/IEC 10646:1993, or [[Unicode]] 1.1. Since its initial release in 1993, GBK has been extended by Microsoft in '''[[Code page 1386|Code page 936/1386]]''', which was then extended into '''[[#GBK 1.0|GBK 1.0]]'''. '''GBK''' is also the IANA-registered internet name for the Microsoft mapping,<ref name=iana>{{cite web|title=Character Sets|url=https://www.iana.org/assignments/character-sets/character-sets.xhtml|accessdate=3 October 2016}}</ref> which differs from other implementations primarily by the single-byte [[euro sign]] at 0x80.\n\n''GB'' abbreviates [[guobiao|Guojia Biaozhun]], which means ''national standard'' in Chinese, while ''K'' stands for ''Extension'' (\u6269\u5c55 ''ku\u00f2zh\u01cen''). GBK not only extended the old standard GB2312 with Traditional Chinese characters, but also with Chinese characters that were simplified after the establishment of GB2312 in 1981. With the arrival of GBK, certain names with characters formerly unrepresentable, like the \u9555 (''r\u00f3ng'') character in former Chinese Premier [[Zhu Rongji|Zhu Rongji's]] name, are now representable.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.microsoft.com/typography/unicode/936.txt |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20021001194325/http://www.microsoft.com/typography/unicode/936.txt |title=Code Page 936 - PRC GBK (XGB) |archivedate=2002-10-01 |url-status=dead}} Conversion map between [[Code page 1386|Codepage 936]] and Unicode. Need manually selecting [[GB18030]] or GBK in browser to view it correctly.</ref> {{As of|2020|04}}, 0.3% of all web pages used GBK,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://w3techs.com/technologies/history_overview/character_encoding |title=Historical trends in the usage of character encodings, April 2020 |publisher=W3techs.com |date= |accessdate=2020-04-11}}</ref> that is when marked as such, but all major web browsers decode documents marked as e.g. \"{{nowrap|[[GB 2312]]}}\" or \"[[GB2312]]\" as if they were marked \"gbk\" (while not all do so for pages marked \"GB_2312\"),<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.w3.org/International/tests/repo/results/encoding-dbl-byte-labels.en.html|title=Encoding: Summarized test results|website=www.w3.org|access-date=2019-11-15}}</ref> and GBK and the subset encoding {{nowrap|GB 2312}} have a combined <!-- 0.3% + 0.5% --> 0.8% share.\n\n==History==\nIn 1993, the [[Unicode]] 1.1 standard was released, including 20,902 characters used in [[mainland China]], [[Taiwan]], [[Japan]] and [[Korea]].  Following this, China released GB13000.1-93, the [[Guobiao standard]] equivalent of Unicode 1.1.\n\n{{anchor|1993}}The '''GBK''' character set was defined in 1993 as an extension of [[GB2312]]-80, while also including the characters of GB13000.1-93 through the unused codepoints available in GB2312.  Hence GBK is backward compatible with GB2312.\n\n{{anchor|cp936}}Microsoft implemented GBK in [[Windows 95]] and [[Windows NT 3.51]] as '''[[Code page 1386|Code Page 936]]'''.  While GBK was never an official standard, widespread usage of Windows 95 led to GBK becoming the ''de facto'' standard. While GBK included all the Chinese characters defined in Unicode 1.1 and GB13000.1-93, these standards used different code tables. The primary reason for its existence was simply to bridge the gap between GB2312-80 and GB13000.1-93.\n\n{{anchor|GBK 1.0}}In 1995, China National Information Technology Standardization Technical Committee set down the Chinese Internal Code Extension Specification ({{lang-zh|s=\u6c49\u5b57\u5185\u7801\u6269\u5c55\u89c4\u8303 (GBK)|p=H\u00e0nz\u00ec N\u00e8im\u01ce Ku\u00f2zh\u01cen Gu\u012bf\u00e0n (GBK)}}), Version 1.0, known as '''GBK&nbsp;1.0''', which is a slight extension of Codepage 936. The newly added 95 characters were not found in GB&nbsp;13000.1-1993, and were provisionally assigned Unicode [[Private Use Areas|PUA]] code points.<ref name=\"gb18030-2005\">{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/GB18030-2005|title=GB 18030-2005: Information Technology\u2014Chinese coded character set|last=Standardization Administration of China (SAC)|date=2005-11-18}}</ref>{{Rp|534}}\n\nMicrosoft later added the [[euro sign]] to Code page 936 and assigned the code 0x80 to it. This is not a valid code point in GBK&nbsp;1.0.\n\n{{anchor|gb18030}}In 2000, the [[GB18030]]-2000 standard was released, superseding yet maintaining compatibility with GBK&nbsp;1.0. It increased the number of definitions of Chinese characters and extended the number of possible characters through the implementation of four-byte character spaces. The subset of GB&nbsp;18030 consisting of one-byte and two-byte characters is sometimes also referred to as '''GBK'''. Mapping to Unicode has been slightly changed, though, as some characters are now defined in Unicode. In the most up-to-date form of the standard, GB&nbsp;18030-2005, only 24<ref>GB 18030-2005 Standard p.9, 79</ref> characters are still mapped to Unicode PUA (see [[GB 18030#PUA]].)\n\nIn 2002, '''GBK''' was registered as an IANA charset; the registration uses [[Code page 1386|code page 936]] mapping as well as CP936/MS936 aliases, but refers to GBK&nbsp;1.0 specification.<ref name=iana/> {{anchor|W3C}}[[W3C]]'s technical recommendation published in 2015<ref>{{cite web|title=Encoding Standard # gbk-encoder|url=https://www.w3.org/TR/encoding/#gbk-encoder|website=W3C|accessdate=2016-10-02}}</ref> defines a '''GBK''' encoder as a GB&nbsp;18030 encoder with a single-byte euro sign and without four-byte sequences.\n\n==Encoding==\nA character is encoded as 1 or 2 bytes.  A byte in the range <code>00</code>\u2013<code>7F</code> is a single byte that means the same thing as it does in [[ASCII]].  Strictly speaking, there are 95 characters and 33 control codes in this range.\n\nA byte with the high bit set indicates that it is the first of 2 bytes.  Loosely speaking, the first byte is in the range <code>81</code>\u2013<code>FE</code> (that is, never <code>80</code> or <code>FF</code>), and the second byte is <code>40</code>\u2013<code>A0</code> except <code>7F</code> for some areas and <code>A1</code>\u2013<code>FE</code> for others.\n\nMore specifically, the following ranges of bytes are defined:\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|+GBK Encoding Ranges\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|range || rowspan=\"2\"|byte 1 || rowspan=\"2\"|byte 2 || rowspan=\"2\"|code points || colspan=\"4\"|characters\n|-\n!GB 18030 || GBK 1.0 || Codepage 936 || GB 2312\n|-\n|Level [[GB2312 Blocks#Block 1-9: Signs|GBK/1]] || <code>A1</code>\u2013<code>A9</code> || <code>A1</code>\u2013<code>FE</code>\n|align=\"right\"|846 || style=\"text-align:right;\"|718<ref name=gb18030-2005/>{{rp|8&ndash;10}} || style=\"text-align:right;\"|717 || style=\"text-align:right;\"|715 || style=\"text-align:right;\"|682\n|-\n|Level [[GBK/2]] || <code>B0</code>\u2013<code>F7</code> || <code>A1</code>\u2013<code>FE</code> || style=\"text-align:right;\"|6,768 || colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:right;\"|6,763 || style=\"text-align:right;\"|6,763 || style=\"text-align:right;\"|6,763\n|-\n|Level GBK/3 || <code>81</code>\u2013<code>A0</code> || <code>40</code>\u2013<code>FE</code> except <code>7F</code>|| style=\"text-align:right;\"|6,080 || colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:right;\"|6,080 || style=\"text-align:right;\"|6,080 || rowspan=\"6\"|\n|-\n|Level GBK/4 || <code>AA</code>\u2013<code>FE</code> || <code>40</code>\u2013<code>A0</code> except <code>7F</code> || style=\"text-align:right;\"|8,160 || colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:right;\"|8,160 || style=\"text-align:right;\"|8,080\n|-\n|Level [[GBK/5]] || <code>A8</code>\u2013<code>A9</code> || <code>40</code>\u2013<code>A0</code> except <code>7F</code> || style=\"text-align:right;\"|192 || colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:right;\"|166 || style=\"text-align:right;\"|153\n|-\n|user-defined 1<ref name=gb18030-2005/> || <code>AA</code>\u2013<code>AF</code> || <code>A1</code>\u2013<code>FE</code> || style=\"text-align:right;\"|564 || colspan=\"4\" rowspan=\"3\"|\n|-\n|user-defined 2 || <code>F8</code>\u2013<code>FE</code> || <code>A1</code>\u2013<code>FE</code> || style=\"text-align:right;\"|658\n|-\n|user-defined 3 || <code>A1</code>\u2013<code>A7</code> || <code>40</code>\u2013<code>A0</code> except <code>7F</code> || style=\"text-align:right;\"|672\n|-\n!total: || || || style=\"text-align:right;\"|23,940 || style=\"text-align:right;\"|21,887 || style=\"text-align:right;\"|21,886 || style=\"text-align:right;\"|21,791 || style=\"text-align:right;\"|7,445\n|}\n\n===Layout diagram===\nIn graphical form, the following figure shows the space of all 64K possible 2-byte codes.  Green and yellow areas are assigned GBK codepoints, red are for user-defined characters.  The uncolored areas are invalid byte combinations.\n\n[[Image:GBK encoding.svg]]\n\n==Relationship to other encodings==\nThe areas indicated in the previous section as GBK/1 and GBK/2, taken by themselves, is simply GB2312-80 in its usual encoding, GBK/1 being the non-hanzi region and GBK/2 the hanzi region.  GB2312, or more properly the EUC-CN encoding thereof, takes a pair of bytes from the range <code>A1</code>\u2013<code>FE</code>, like any 94\u00b2 ISO-2022 character set loaded into GR.  This corresponds to the lower-right quarter of the illustration above.  However, GB2312 does not assign any code points to the rows located at <code>AA</code>\u2013<code>B0</code> and <code>F8</code>\u2013<code>FE</code>, even though it had staked out the territory.  GBK added extensions to these rows.  You can see that the two gaps were filled in with user-defined areas.\n\nMore significantly, GBK extended the range of the bytes.  Having two-byte characters in the ISO-2022 GR range gives a limit of 94\u00b2=8,836 possibilities.  Abandoning the ISO-2022 model of strict regions for graphics and control characters, but retaining the feature of low bytes being 1-byte characters and pairs of high bytes denoting a character, you could potentially have 128\u00b2=16,384 positions.  GBK takes part of that, extending the range from <code>A1</code>\u2013<code>FE</code> (94 choices for each byte) to <code>81</code>\u2013<code>FE</code> (126 choices) for the first byte and <code>40</code>\u2013<code>FE</code> (191 choices) for the second byte, for a total of 24,066 positions.\n\nMicrosoft's Code Page 936 is generally thought of as being GBK.<ref name=iana/>  However, the [[GB 18030#History|95 PUA characters]] added in GBK 1.0 are not included in Code Page 936.  Code Page 936 also has a single-byte [[euro sign]] at 0x80 which GBK 1.0 doesn't have.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Scherer |first1=Markus |title=Re: Fun with GBK & GB2312 |url=http://unicode.org/mail-arch/unicode-ml/y2002-m01/0042.html |website=Unicode Mail List Archive |accessdate=4 March 2020 |date=4 January 2002}}</ref>\n\nGBK's successor, [[GB18030]]-2000, uses the remaining range available to the second byte ({{code|30}}&ndash;{{code|39}}) to further expand the number of possibilities while retaining GBK as a subset.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://icu-project.org/repos/icu/data/trunk/charset/source/gb18030/gbkuni30.txt ICU's Authoritative GBK mapping] - part of [https://ssl.icu-project.org/repos/icu/data/trunk/charset/source/gb18030/gb18030.html GB18030 data]\n*[http://www.microsoft.com/globaldev/reference/dbcs/936.mspx Microsoft Reference page for GBK]\n*[https://www.unicode.org/Public/MAPPINGS/VENDORS/MICSFT/WINDOWS/CP936.TXT  Mapping of GBK to Unicode ] N.B.: this is Microsoft code page 936, which contains entries for 21791 double-byte code points, 96 single-byte graphic characters, and 33 control characters.  This is not exactly the same as GBK which has 21886 characters.\n*[http://www.khngai.com/chinese/charmap/tblgbk.php?page=0 GBK Code Table] N.B. This gbk-encoded page shows the available coding space totally populated except for 2 places, for a total of 32256 glyphs (32352 with the implied single-byte ASCII codes not illustrated), which is more than 23940 or 21886. Actual rendering of this table depends on your browser's GBK decoder.\n\n{{CJK computing}}\n{{character encoding}}\n\n[[Category:Character sets]]\n[[Category:Windows code pages]]\n[[Category:Encodings of Asian languages]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Simplified Chinese character encoding}}\n{{refimprove|date=October 2016}}<!-- We need some good GBK 1.0 & 1993 GBK data. All I can find is CP936. -->\n{{Infobox character encoding\n| name = Guojia Biaozhun Kuozhan (GBK)\n| mime = GBK\n| alias = [[Code page 1386|CP936]], MS936, windows-936, csGBK\n| image = GBK encoding.svg\n| caption = Layout of GBK ([[#Layout diagram|see below]] for a larger copy of this diagram)\n| standard = GBK 1.0\n| lang = Primarily used